<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-614-692  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 614 692.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  May 15 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MCI testifies against further deregulation. (MCI CommunicationsCorp., Bell Operating Companies)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   MCI Communications Corp. (officials and employees).andO;Ticker:    MCIC.andO;Topic:     United States. Congress. House. Subcommittee on TelecommunicationsBell Regional Holding CompaniesLegal IssuesGovernment RegulationDeregulationTelephone companies.andO;Person:    Eidenberg, Eugene (evidence).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MCI TESTIFIES AGAINST FURTHER DEREGULATION WASHINGTON, D.C., U.S.A., 1990 MAY10 (NB) -- Deregulating the Bell Operating Companies would be a disaster forconsumers, according to the company which was the biggest beneficiary of the1984 Bell break-up.andM;Eugene Eidenberg, MCI executive vice president, told the House Subcommitteeon Telecommunications a bill submitted by its staff would &quot;create a mechanismthat would allow the Regional Bell Operating Companies to enter thecompetitive markets from which they are restricted while, at the same time,continuing to operate their local exchange services on a monopoly basis.andP;  Itis a prescription that will open the door to the same anti-competitivepractices that led to the antitrust case in the first place.andP;  You shouldn'tlet that happen.&quot;andM;The draft bill would create a mechanism that would allow Regional BellOperating Companies to enter the information services and telephone equipmentmanufacturing businesses, from which they're presently prohibited.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900511/Press Contact: MCI, John Houser, 1- 800-289-0073)</TEXT></DOC>